Estimates from community samples indicate that between 9 and 14% of adults in the USA would meet diagnostic criteria
         criteria
       for at least one specific PD (Eaton & Greene, 
         2018
      ). However, some have argued these estimates may be underestimated as individuals with PDs are not always aware of the impact their behavior has on other people and may be unable to identify the presence of their own maladaptive traits (Huprich et al., 
         2011
      ). Prevalence rates of PDs are generally higher in high-income countries compared with low- and middle-income countries (Winsper et al., 
         2020
      ). This may be attributable to variations in behavioral norms across countries (e. g., individualistic versus collectivist societies) or cultural differences that impact the
         the
       validity of diagnostic traits and categories.
